05211nam a22008055i 9780812206357DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979741174  a97808122063577 a10.9783/97808122063572doi  a(DE-B1597)449599  a(OCoLC)822017770  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a615.852095611 aDole, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHealing Secular Life :bLoss and Devotion in Modern Turkey /cChristopher Dole. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b18 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Ethnography00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Medicine and the Will to Civilization -- tChapter 2. Healing Difference at the Limits of Community -- tChapter 3. Hagiographies of the Living: Saintly Speech and Other Wonders of Secular Life -- tChapter 4. The Therapeutics of Piety: Ethics, Markets, Value -- tChapter 5. A Malaise of Fracturing Dreams: The Care of Relations -- tChapter 6. Healing Secular Life: Two Regimes of Loss -- tConclusion: Fragments -- tAppendix: Genres of Healing -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn contemporary Turkey—a democratic, secular, and predominantly Muslim nation—the religious healer is a controversial figure. Attracting widespread condemnation, religious healers are derided as exploiters of the sick and vulnerable, discredited forms of Islamic and medical authority, and superstitious relics of a pre-modern era. Yet all sorts of people, and not just the desperately ill, continue to seek them out. After years of research with healers and their patients in working-class neighborhoods of urban Turkey, anthropologist Christopher Dole concludes that the religious healer should be regarded not as an exception to Turkey's secular modern development but as one of its defining figures. Healing Secular Life demonstrates that religious healing and secularism in fact have a set of common stakes in the ordering of lives and the remaking of worlds.Linking the history of medical reforms and scientific literacy campaigns to contemporary efforts of Qur'anic healers to treat people afflicted by spirits and living saints through whom deceased political leaders speak, Healing Secular Life approaches stories of healing and being healed as settings for examining the everyday social intimacies of secular political rule. This ethnography of loss, care, and politics reveals not only that the authority of the religious healer is deeply embedded within the history of secular modern reform in Turkey but also that personal narratives of suffering and affliction are inseparable from the story of a nation seeking to recover from the violence of its own secular past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHealersxLegal status, laws, etczTurkey. 0aSecularismzTurkey. 0aSpiritual healingxPolitical aspectszTurkey. 4aFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041361808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220635740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812206357423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812206357.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Comp